00:00:02,728 --> 00:00:04,229
La cucaracha!

2
00:00:04,296 --> 00:00:07,732
♪ Oh, oh! La cucaracha,
la cucaracha ♪

3
00:00:07,799 --> 00:00:09,350
♪ Hey! Hey!

4
00:00:09,435 --> 00:00:11,802
♪ Ya no puede caminar

5
00:00:11,854 --> 00:00:13,938
♪ Porque le falta

6
00:00:13,989 --> 00:00:15,356
♪ Porque
le falta ♪

7
00:00:15,441 --> 00:00:16,190
♪ Hey! Hey!

8
00:00:16,275 --> 00:00:18,476
♪ Marihuana que fumar

9
00:00:18,527 --> 00:00:20,778
♪ Yo estoy harto
de que me digan... ♪

10
00:00:20,829 --> 00:00:23,448
<i>WILL:
I should have known by the
looks on my students' faces</i>

11
00:00:23,499 --> 00:00:25,316
<i>that I'd really stepped in it.</i>

12
00:00:25,367 --> 00:00:28,002
<i>My yearly rendition of "La
Cucaracha"on Taco Tuesday</i>

13
00:00:28,087 --> 00:00:29,654
<i>used to be such a hit.</i>

14
00:00:29,705 --> 00:00:31,756
<i>The truth is, I'm ashamed.</i>

15
00:00:31,823 --> 00:00:33,791
<i>To be a teacher
is to offer students</i>

16
00:00:33,842 --> 00:00:35,660
<i>a gateway to the future,
and I blew it.</i>

17
00:00:35,711 --> 00:00:37,679
<i>How could I have
become so out of touch?</i>

18
00:00:37,763 --> 00:00:39,681
(school bell ringing)

19
00:00:39,765 --> 00:00:40,848
William...

20
00:00:40,933 --> 00:00:42,267
What do you mean,
you received complaints?

21
00:00:42,334 --> 00:00:44,435
Who complained?
I can't tell you that.

22
00:00:44,503 --> 00:00:47,171
But I can tell you that
your teaching skills

23
00:00:47,222 --> 00:00:49,557
have been seriously
brought into question.

24
00:00:49,642 --> 00:00:51,726
Look, I-I know I'm not
a native Spanish speaker.

25
00:00:51,810 --> 00:00:53,811
Sometimes I get a little
tripped up with the...
William.

26
00:00:53,862 --> 00:00:55,813
Will you please remove
that enormous sombrero

27
00:00:55,864 --> 00:00:57,615
so I can break
it down for you.

28
00:00:57,683 --> 00:00:59,817
As you may have heard,

29
00:00:59,868 --> 00:01:01,319
our history teacher,
Mrs. Hagberg,

30
00:01:01,370 --> 00:01:03,488
has been forced into retirement

31
00:01:03,539 --> 00:01:05,239
due to some memory problems.

32
00:01:05,324 --> 00:01:09,661
And that's how Germany
won the Second World War.

33
00:01:09,712 --> 00:01:11,996
Hagberg was a tenured
teacher at this school

34
00:01:12,047 --> 00:01:13,548
for over 40 years.

35
00:01:13,632 --> 00:01:17,168
Her departure means there's
an open tenured position

36
00:01:17,219 --> 00:01:18,336
here at McKinley.

37
00:01:18,387 --> 00:01:20,505
Oh, Principal Figgins...

38
00:01:20,556 --> 00:01:21,973
Emma and I just got engaged.

39
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:24,258
We'll be starting a family soon.
I need that tenure.

40
00:01:24,343 --> 00:01:26,561
And I would love
to give it to you, William.

41
00:01:26,645 --> 00:01:28,596
But you're only one
of several teachers

42
00:01:28,681 --> 00:01:30,815
I'm considering
for this position.

43
00:01:30,882 --> 00:01:33,318
And to be frank, you have
a public relations problem.

44
00:01:33,385 --> 00:01:35,069
If you want the tenure,

45
00:01:35,154 --> 00:01:36,387
you've got to turn it
around in the class.

46
00:01:36,438 --> 00:01:38,222
O-Okay.
How do I do that?

47
00:01:38,273 --> 00:01:39,490
You're a Spanish teacher.

48
00:01:39,558 --> 00:01:41,275
Maybe you should try
learning Spanish.

49
00:01:45,597 --> 00:01:46,564
(school bell ringing)

50
00:01:46,615 --> 00:01:47,832
Señor Martinez?

51
00:01:47,899 --> 00:01:51,235
You can call me David.

52
00:01:51,286 --> 00:01:52,587
David, I am thrilled

53
00:01:52,671 --> 00:01:54,905
that Spanish has so many
different ways to say

54
00:01:54,957 --> 00:01:58,075
"to be," but right now
what I need to do

55
00:01:58,127 --> 00:02:00,178
is to learn how to say,

56
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:03,047
"Stop using my toilet,"
to my maid.

57
00:02:03,098 --> 00:02:05,967
I was hoping you could tell me
what the word "gordita" means.

58
00:02:06,051 --> 00:02:08,419
I know we're all here
for different reasons.

59
00:02:08,470 --> 00:02:10,087
Most of you need your GEDs,

60
00:02:10,139 --> 00:02:12,023
some of you want to
go to Cabo San Lucas

61
00:02:12,091 --> 00:02:13,608
and order like a local.

62
00:02:13,692 --> 00:02:16,694
But did you know that the U.S.
census believe that by 2030

63
00:02:16,762 --> 00:02:19,030
the majority of Americans
will use Spanish

64
00:02:19,097 --> 00:02:20,598
as their first language?

65
00:02:20,649 --> 00:02:22,533
You're not here
learning a language.

66
00:02:22,601 --> 00:02:25,703
You're here 'cause you're smart.
And you're forward thinkers.

67
00:02:25,771 --> 00:02:27,121
I'm sorry. I'm trying to listen,

68
00:02:27,206 --> 00:02:28,373
but you got some
beautiful teeth.

69
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:29,273
(chuckles)

70
00:02:39,117 --> 00:02:40,168
<i>Asi que repiten conmigo.</i>

71
00:02:40,252 --> 00:02:41,085
Come on, repeat with me.

72
00:02:51,330 --> 00:02:52,680
(school bell rings)

73
00:02:52,765 --> 00:02:54,148
DAVID:
Very good. Thank you so much.

74
00:02:54,233 --> 00:02:56,100
Remember, roll those "R"s.
(rolling "R"s)

75
00:02:56,151 --> 00:02:57,968
(rolling "R"s)
Exactly.

76
00:02:58,020 --> 00:02:59,070
Hey, I'm Will Schuester.

77
00:02:59,137 --> 00:03:01,355
I teach Spanish here
during the day.

78
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:03,641
<i>Can I buy you a cup of café?</i>

79
00:03:03,692 --> 00:03:04,975
(laughing):
Sure.

80
00:03:05,027 --> 00:03:06,611
There's something kind of
fun and rebellious

81
00:03:06,662 --> 00:03:07,745
about being here at night.

82
00:03:07,813 --> 00:03:09,714
It's depressing.

83
00:03:09,782 --> 00:03:11,649
No offense.
No. No, um...

84
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:13,818
Why don't you get a job
teaching regular high school?

85
00:03:13,869 --> 00:03:15,720
Have you seen the news?
Budgets are being cut,

86
00:03:15,788 --> 00:03:17,355
there's a hiring freeze...

87
00:03:22,594 --> 00:03:24,729
You know, could you maybe
say that a little slower?

88
00:03:24,797 --> 00:03:26,380
I think your accent's
throwing me off.

89
00:03:26,465 --> 00:03:27,765
W-Where you from?
Ohio.

90
00:03:27,833 --> 00:03:29,667
But my parents are from Chile,

91
00:03:29,718 --> 00:03:31,469
and we only spoke Spanish
in the house, growing up.

92
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:32,937
Oh.

93
00:03:33,005 --> 00:03:35,005
How-how long have you been,
uh, working here?

94
00:03:35,057 --> 00:03:36,858
Just a few months.
This is...

95
00:03:36,942 --> 00:03:38,976
actually the beginning
of my career change.

96
00:03:39,027 --> 00:03:41,679
For the last six years,
I was a tooth model.

97
00:03:41,730 --> 00:03:43,364
It's like a hand model,
but with your teeth.

98
00:03:44,750 --> 00:03:46,684
Man, your teeth
are really white.

99
00:03:46,735 --> 00:03:49,570
Yeah, no coffee,
no cigarettes, no beets.

100
00:03:49,655 --> 00:03:51,038
I was the top tooth model
in the country.

101
00:03:51,123 --> 00:03:53,574
Colgate, Crest Whitestrips,
Sensodyne...

102
00:03:53,659 --> 00:03:54,826
Whenever they needed a smile
for their advertisement,

103
00:03:54,877 --> 00:03:56,577
they would call on
Dave Martinez.

104
00:03:56,662 --> 00:03:58,496
Wow, that sounds like
a great gig.

105
00:03:58,547 --> 00:04:00,364
What... why'd you stop?

106
00:04:00,415 --> 00:04:01,716
Well, one day I...

107
00:04:01,800 --> 00:04:04,368
I realized I was spending
so much time flossing, I...

108
00:04:04,419 --> 00:04:06,704
I was missing my life.
I want to make a difference

109
00:04:06,755 --> 00:04:08,089
that lasts longer
than a grin, you know?

110
00:04:08,173 --> 00:04:10,641
I-I want to teach kids.

111
00:04:10,709 --> 00:04:13,344
I want to give them
something useful.

112
00:04:13,395 --> 00:04:15,813
Something they can...
they can take with them

113
00:04:15,881 --> 00:04:17,214
their whole lives.

114
00:04:17,266 --> 00:04:18,683
<i>I want to help them
find their duende.</i>

115
00:04:18,750 --> 00:04:19,984
<i>You know duende, right?</i>

116
00:04:20,051 --> 00:04:21,051
Of course.

117
00:04:21,103 --> 00:04:22,753
<i>Duende, yeah.</i>

118
00:04:22,821 --> 00:04:24,655
Now, you also teach
Glee Club, right?

119
00:04:24,723 --> 00:04:26,908
I do.
You see, that's...
that's inspiring.

120
00:04:26,992 --> 00:04:29,861
I actually wanted to try forming
the night school Glee Club,

121
00:04:29,912 --> 00:04:32,029
but meeting after school
means 2:00 in the morning.

122
00:04:32,080 --> 00:04:33,998
Ah, right.
(laughs)
I love to sing.

123
00:04:34,065 --> 00:04:37,735
<i>I actually learned English
watching reruns of Solid Gold.</i>

124
00:04:37,786 --> 00:04:38,870
Wait. You're serious?

125
00:04:38,921 --> 00:04:40,505
Yeah. They-they've done
studies on it.

126
00:04:40,572 --> 00:04:43,207
The brain takes in information,
like a new language,

127
00:04:43,258 --> 00:04:45,843
or a math equation,
much more quickly

128
00:04:45,911 --> 00:04:47,745
and retains it better,
when that information

129
00:04:47,813 --> 00:04:49,347
is delivered through music.

130
00:04:49,414 --> 00:04:52,583
<i>Well, there's a lot of
duende involved, too.</i>

131
00:04:54,052 --> 00:04:55,753
You know what I would do
if I was teaching Glee Club?

132
00:04:55,804 --> 00:04:57,638
Latin music. Think about it.

133
00:04:57,723 --> 00:04:59,390
You get those kids
singing in Spanish,

134
00:04:59,458 --> 00:05:00,625
and they'll be
learning the language

135
00:05:00,692 --> 00:05:02,627
without even realizing it.

136
00:05:02,694 --> 00:05:05,246
<i>WILL:
If I could have some of my
Glee kids speaking Spanish</i>

137
00:05:05,314 --> 00:05:07,932
<i>by the end of the week, it'd be
a hell of an accomplishment.</i>

138
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,184
<i>That's Teacher of the Year
stuff.</i>

139
00:05:10,252 --> 00:05:12,470
Twice a day, you boys stain

140
00:05:12,538 --> 00:05:15,156
your mother's drapes,
or befoul a gym sock

141
00:05:15,240 --> 00:05:17,158
that has to jump from the hamper
straight into therapy.

142
00:05:17,242 --> 00:05:18,993
SUE:
Why not head on down
to the clinic,

143
00:05:19,077 --> 00:05:21,495
and put your virile
teen years to good use?

144
00:05:21,580 --> 00:05:23,381
You'll have five bucks more
than when you walked in,

145
00:05:23,448 --> 00:05:26,250
and the gratitude of
lonely ovaries everywhere.

146
00:05:26,301 --> 00:05:28,219
But not you. You can
keep tossing your tissues

147
00:05:28,286 --> 00:05:30,304
into the trash.
I was in an accident.

148
00:05:30,389 --> 00:05:32,740
Still. Same goes for you,
Porcelain.

149
00:05:32,808 --> 00:05:34,792
Let the strangeness
end with you.

150
00:05:34,843 --> 00:05:37,011
What's going on, Sue?

151
00:05:37,095 --> 00:05:40,014
Well, William, I'm just
trying to instill

152
00:05:40,098 --> 00:05:41,799
the spirit of giving
in your students.

153
00:05:41,850 --> 00:05:44,435
No, honestly, I, uh...

154
00:05:44,486 --> 00:05:47,605
was a little bit dismayed
by the quality of men

155
00:05:47,656 --> 00:05:49,740
holding Dixie cups
down at the sperm bank

156
00:05:49,808 --> 00:05:51,125
this morning.

157
00:05:51,193 --> 00:05:52,526
Zero viable options.

158
00:05:52,611 --> 00:05:54,996
<i>Looked like the cast from
Ice Road Truckers.</i>

159
00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:57,915
So I thought it'd be best
if I found a sperm donor here.

160
00:05:57,983 --> 00:05:59,200
H-Hold on a second.

161
00:05:59,284 --> 00:06:00,251
You're serious?

162
00:06:00,318 --> 00:06:01,953
Yes, William.

163
00:06:02,004 --> 00:06:04,005
I have decided to have a child.

164
00:06:04,089 --> 00:06:05,673
(laughs)

165
00:06:07,158 --> 00:06:08,542
Um, wow.

166
00:06:08,627 --> 00:06:10,761
I guess I just never saw you
as the mothering type.

167
00:06:10,829 --> 00:06:12,513
Well, I resent that, William.

168
00:06:12,598 --> 00:06:14,615
I have a very strong
mothering instinct.

169
00:06:14,683 --> 00:06:16,350
I had it with my sister.

170
00:06:16,435 --> 00:06:17,885
I have it with Becky Jackson.

171
00:06:17,970 --> 00:06:21,222
I like to think I play
a parenting role in her life.

172
00:06:21,306 --> 00:06:25,059
And like so many women who
chose career over family,

173
00:06:25,143 --> 00:06:27,878
I've decided to take my life
in a different direction

174
00:06:27,946 --> 00:06:30,848
while there's still time.

175
00:06:30,899 --> 00:06:32,149
Are you sure
that's even possible?

176
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:34,402
Yes, William, I am sure.

177
00:06:34,486 --> 00:06:38,072
You see, I had my eggs
frozen in the late '70s.

178
00:06:38,156 --> 00:06:40,741
They didn't even have that
technology in the late '70s.

179
00:06:40,826 --> 00:06:43,327
I know.
I did it myself.

180
00:06:43,378 --> 00:06:46,497
Oh...
The good people at Kroger
have been keeping a box

181
00:06:46,548 --> 00:06:48,332
of my championship ova

182
00:06:48,383 --> 00:06:49,834
cooling in their meat locker.

183
00:06:49,885 --> 00:06:51,252
And what with
the financial security

184
00:06:51,336 --> 00:06:53,721
that will be afforded me
by the end of the week...

185
00:06:53,805 --> 00:06:56,040
I am finally ready

186
00:06:56,091 --> 00:06:58,426
to start a family.

187
00:06:58,510 --> 00:07:00,061
Now, I don't know if
you've heard, William,

188
00:07:00,145 --> 00:07:01,228
but there's a tenured position

189
00:07:01,313 --> 00:07:02,980
opening up at our school.

190
00:07:03,048 --> 00:07:05,349
And I'm a shoe-in.
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

191
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:08,052
What makes you so sure you're
the one who's gonna get tenure?

192
00:07:08,103 --> 00:07:09,553
Seniority, William.

193
00:07:09,604 --> 00:07:11,939
I'm first in line, and also,
I'm a proven champion.

194
00:07:12,024 --> 00:07:15,910
And now seeing as how I find
bald infants terrifying,

195
00:07:15,994 --> 00:07:17,995
I'm going to need a few
ounces of your baby gravy

196
00:07:18,063 --> 00:07:20,865
to ensure Sue Sylvester Jr. is
born with a full head of hair.

197
00:07:20,916 --> 00:07:22,616
Coach?

198
00:07:22,701 --> 00:07:26,170
Principal Figgins wants to
see you in his office.

199
00:07:26,237 --> 00:07:29,040
Looks like I got my tenure.

200
00:07:29,091 --> 00:07:31,509
Cheerleading magazines
are right here.

201
00:07:31,576 --> 00:07:33,410
Have fun.

202
00:07:38,050 --> 00:07:39,717
Complaints?

203
00:07:39,768 --> 00:07:42,219
Who's complaining about
my teaching style?

204
00:07:42,270 --> 00:07:44,355
I can't tell you that, Sue.

205
00:07:44,422 --> 00:07:46,223
A student who shall
remain anonymous.

206
00:07:46,274 --> 00:07:47,274
Well, then, who's this?

207
00:07:48,727 --> 00:07:50,778
Sue, this is the talented
and enchanting

208
00:07:50,862 --> 00:07:52,947
Olympian Roz Washington.

209
00:07:53,031 --> 00:07:54,165
Coach of the McKinley

210
00:07:54,232 --> 00:07:56,200
synchronized swimming team.

211
00:07:56,267 --> 00:07:58,486
Roz approached me with
some constructive criticism

212
00:07:58,570 --> 00:08:00,071
about your lagging Cheerios!

213
00:08:00,122 --> 00:08:01,539
Why should I listen
to this woman

214
00:08:01,606 --> 00:08:02,773
give me notes

215
00:08:02,824 --> 00:08:04,158
about my Cheerios?

216
00:08:04,242 --> 00:08:06,410
Because Cheerios! didn't
win Nationals last year, Sue.

217
00:08:06,461 --> 00:08:09,613
And remember, you're on my short
list for the tenured position.

218
00:08:09,664 --> 00:08:11,549
And tenured teachers
are team players.

219
00:08:11,616 --> 00:08:14,135
Well, let me tell you
why ticket sales are down

220
00:08:14,219 --> 00:08:16,504
at sporting events.
This school got cheerleaders

221
00:08:16,588 --> 00:08:18,973
doing broke-ass moves
from the 1950s.

222
00:08:19,057 --> 00:08:20,891
Hm.
Why don't you just admit

223
00:08:20,959 --> 00:08:23,460
that you're past your
competitive edge, Sue Sylvester,

224
00:08:23,512 --> 00:08:24,562
and let this young

225
00:08:24,629 --> 00:08:28,482
bronze-medal winner
add some crunk

226
00:08:28,567 --> 00:08:30,401
to the ba-dunk-a-dunk?

227
00:08:32,687 --> 00:08:34,655
(school bell ringing)

228
00:08:34,740 --> 00:08:35,656
WILL:
All right, guys!

229
00:08:35,741 --> 00:08:37,108
Let me ask you something.

230
00:08:37,159 --> 00:08:40,244
Where do you think you'll
be in the year 2030?

231
00:08:40,311 --> 00:08:41,996
RACHEL & KURT:
Broadway. Twinsies!

232
00:08:42,080 --> 00:08:43,614
Walking.

233
00:08:43,665 --> 00:08:44,999
In jail, or dead. Or both.

234
00:08:45,083 --> 00:08:46,500
WILL:
Wherever you are,

235
00:08:46,585 --> 00:08:48,786
whatever you're doing, you're
going to need to be able

236
00:08:48,837 --> 00:08:51,288
to speak Spanish.
The reality is, by 2030,

237
00:08:51,339 --> 00:08:52,673
more people on this planet

238
00:08:52,758 --> 00:08:55,059
will be speaking Spanish
than any other language.

239
00:08:55,127 --> 00:08:57,094
The world is changing.
Our culture is changing.

240
00:08:57,162 --> 00:08:58,963
And that needs to be
reflected in here.

241
00:08:59,014 --> 00:09:00,664
So for our next assignment,
we're only doing songs

242
00:09:00,715 --> 00:09:04,501
written or performed by someone
Latin, or of Latin descent.

243
00:09:04,553 --> 00:09:06,353
Or English songs
performed bilingually.

244
00:09:06,438 --> 00:09:07,938
Ooh, I'm bilingual.

245
00:09:08,006 --> 00:09:10,340
, Mr. Shue, though I love
that we're finally getting

246
00:09:10,392 --> 00:09:13,227
all Lima Sound Machine
in here, why now?

247
00:09:13,311 --> 00:09:15,279
Oh, Santana,
because it's long overdue.

248
00:09:15,346 --> 00:09:18,065
The truth is,
